<DOCNO> AP890525-0010 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the university of california at 
berkeley which for years has tried to come up with an ethnically 
fair admissions formula on wednesday announced a standard based on 
high academic performance regardless of race 
the proposal represents a move back to admissions based on 
academic excellence and away from preferential treatment based on 
ethnic background and considerations said robert l bailey a 
member of the academic senate committee that drafted the proposals 
the changes would restore special considerations for students 
eligible for the university of california and are from poor or 
uneducated families a category eliminated in 1984 said sociology 
professor jerome karabel the committees chairman 
the number of berkeley applicants has increased dramatically 
since 1981 creating ferocious competition and giving the 
campus a chance to attract a student body that is both stronger 
academically and diverse socially and economically than ever 
before karabel said 
the number of applicants for approximately 7700 offers of 
admission at berkeley increased from 9006 in 1981 to 22439 in 
1988 according to university figures only about 3400 students 
actually enroll the rest go on to other universities where they 
also applied 
the changes which will take place by the fall of 1991 if 
approved were made in part because of complaints that current 
policies discriminate against asianamerican applicants 
changes in 198384 withdrew automatic admission for all eligible 
students who were also poor a program that benefited a large 
percentage of asian students karabel said 
thursdays report was issued in the wake of a bitter 
controversy on the berkeley campus over allegations of 
discrimination against asianamericans who comprise about 26 
percent of undergraduates karabel said 
berkeley chancellor ira michael heyman and the asian american 
task force on university of california admissions issued a joint 
statement in march that said policies adopted in 198384 were 
unfair 
under the new proposal which must still be approved by the 
administration the proportion of freshmen admitted on the basis of 
outstanding academic records alone would be increased from 40 
percent to 50 percent 
this will ensure that all students with good enough high school 
records to place them in the top half of berkeleys entering class 
will be accepted the committee said 
in california 328 percent of asian high school graduates meet 
uc eligibility requirements compared to 158 percent of whites and 
5 percent of hispanics and 45 percent of blacks 
another 45 percent of the freshmen would be selected from among 
groups given special consideration all of these students will 
have met academic standards for uc admission placing them in the 
top eighth of the states graduating high school seniors 
the changes would add a category of socioeconomically 
disadvantaged to this group which already includes 
underrepresented minorities on campus blacks hispanics and 
indians as well as outstanding athletes and the disabled 
reentry applicants typically older women would also be given 
special consideration 
there will be more disadvantaged white and asian students on 
the campus karabel said 
the addition of the economic disadvantage category is in 
addition to affirmative action based on race not in place of it 
and will not lower the number of underrepresented minorities on 
campus he said 
the remaining 5 percent accepted would be filled by special 
admission students who do not meet admission standards but are 
accepted because their racial or economic background placed them at 
a disadvantage or because they have special talents such as 
athletic or artistic achievements berkeley currently admits 6 
percent of its freshmen on this basis 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

