<TEXT>
the united states gave somalia weapons which 
were used to crush an insurgency then it turned around and sent 
emergency assistance to patch up the victims 
those are the findings of a report by the congressional general 
accounting office which sent a team to somalia to investigate 
allegations of serious human rights abuses and to find out whether 
us aid was used last year against rebels retaliating for the 
abuses 
the us shipment of 1200 m16 automatic rifles and more than 2 
million rounds of ammunition was authorized in november 1986 as 
part of a military aid package to the strategically located african 
country on the shores of the red sea 
but for technical reasons the delivery did not get to somalia 
until june 28 1988 the report found it was immediately trucked 
to hargeisa a town that government troops were trying to retake 
from the rebels according to the gao the watchdog agency of 
congress 
a senior somali military official confirmed that the us 
equipment was distributed to troops in the north and was used 
during the conflict the report said 
the somali military also resorted to using artillery and 
aerial shelling in heavily populated urban centers and about 70 
percent of hargeisa was damaged or destroyed the team found 
starting in august 1988 the us government responded to the 
emergency with 19 million in disaster assistance to help the 
victims of the conflict said the report the assistance included 
a field hospital unit plastic sheeting blankets and food staples 
it said 
the use of the arms to crush the rebel somali national movement 
prompted the administration to suspend further weapons deliveries 
since then the administration has voluntarily limited the 
military assistance programs to nonlethal items including spare 
parts for previously supplied weapons the report said 
state department officials say the united states has stopped 
deliveries in order to encourage the government to negotiate a 
peace agreement with the snm 
although the government has responded to us pressure and 
released more than 300 political prisoners in recent months no 
progress has been made toward talks with the snm partly through 
the rebels fault 
