<TEXT>
the bush administration is coming under 
increasing attack for its plan to build new military reactors in 
south carolina and idaho that could provide far more material for 
nuclear warheads than the pentagon says it will need 
the latest barrage of criticism comes from the general 
accounting office the investigative arm of congress it said 
wednesday that lawmakers were given inaccurate and incomplete 
information about key elements of the plan to build reactors in 
south carolina and idaho 
the gao also questioned whether it was necessary to build the 
reactors which the energy department says would provide 150 
percent of the anticipated need for tritium a radioactive gas used 
to boost the explosive power of nuclear warheads 
the administration wants to build one reactor at the federal 
savannah river site near aiken sc and another at the idaho 
national engineering laboratory near idaho falls it says they 
could be built within 10 years for 68 billion 
the main reason for constructing new reactors is that the only 
existing ones capable of producing tritium all situated at the 
savannah river site are shut down for repairs and safety 
improvements until sometime next year they are 35 years old and 
not expected to run more than another 15 years 
ronald w cochran the energy department official in charge of 
the new reactor program told a special panel of the house armed 
services committee on wednesday that the tritium supply outlook was 
a major national security issue 
a crisis is at hand robert b barker the defense 
secretarys top adviser on nuclear energy told the panel in a 
written statement without a source of new tritium unilateral 
disarmament is inevitable 
prominent us scientists however have cast doubt on the claim 
that failure to resume tritium production in the next several years 
would hurt us security 
carson mark a former atomic bomb designer told the panel 
tuesday that congress should put off deciding whether to finance 
the construction of the two new reactors he said the united states 
already has more than enough tritium in hand to maintain its 
existing stockpile of approximately 23000 nuclear weapons 
mark said the improved outlook for substantial new reductions in 
us and soviet nuclear arsenals could eliminate the need for new 
tritiumproduction reactors 
he and other scientists have urged the administration to take 
advantage of the forced suspension of us tritium production to 
propose a mutual ussoviet production ban 
energy secretary james d watkins and other administration 
officials have sought to persuade congress that an improved 
capability to make tritium is vital to us security because there 
is no immediate prospect for complete disarmament 
watkins has acknowledged that two new reactors as envisioned by 
the administrations plan would provide more tritium production 
capacity than is needed but he said this would provide insurance 
against possible mechanical failures or other problems such as the 
safety questions raised about the existing older reactors 
j dexter peach an assistant gao comptroller general said the 
administration needs to take a closer look at the budget 
implications of the tworeactor approach he noted that the energy 
department already faces a daunting task in finding an estimated 
100 billion or more to clean up the environmental damage caused by 
40 years of nuclear weapons production at existing sites 
peach said the energy department in its august 1988 report to 
congress on the new reactor plan had inaccurately estimated the 
costs involved and the amount of time it would take to get the 
reactors running peach did not give his own cost estimate but said 
the 10year construction schedule was at least 2 years too short 
