<TEXT>
public schools must provide education for all 
handicapped children no matter how severe the disability or how 
little they might benefit a federal appeals panel has ruled in 
reversing a lower court 
the ruling wednesday by the threejudge panel of the 1st us 
circuit of appeals was in a new hampshire case but it could affect 
public schools and handicapped children throughout the country 
judge hugh bownes wrote the decision that reversed a ruling last 
year in us district court in new hampshire 
the appeals court said the 1975 education for all handicapped 
children act mandates an appropriate public education for all 
handicapped children regardless of the level of achievement that 
such children might attain 
the judges also said a school district has a duty to provide 
an educational program for every handicapped child in the district 
regardless of the severity of the handicap 
the case began in 1974 with a complaint filed in the federal 
court in new hampshire on behalf of a boy identified as timothy w 
the complaint alleged his rights under federal and new hampshire 
law were violated by the rochester nh school district when it 
said the boy was not eligible for special education 
at later hearings the boys mother and therapists testified 
that timothy could hear see bright light and respond to music 
touching and talking 
but a developmental pediatrician testified timothy did not 
have educational needs and could not benefit from an education 
the district court ruled last july that federal law mandates 
that before a child receives a special education a determination 
must be made whether the child will benefit from it 
the court concluded that timothy could not be educated 
the appeals court remanded its ruling to the district court 
until the school district develops a suitable individualized 
program for timothy 
rochester school superintendent raymond yeagley said the appeals 
court decision will force the school district to shift resources 
from students who could benefit from education and focus them on 
less capable students 
school districts are getting to the point they are asked to do 
everything and spend more on education services than education 
said gwendolyn gregory deputy general counsel of the national 
school boards association in washington 
the association had filed a brief in support of the rochester 
school district 
ms gregory said the appeals court decision could make a school 
liable for such medical services as physical therapy that could be 
considered education 
but lorraine greiff spokeswoman for the massachusetts office of 
handicapped affairs hailed the decision 
i think its terrific how can you prove who is going to 
thrive and who isnt she said 
ronald k lospennato the new hampshire lawyer who represented 
timothy and the disability rights center said it simply 
reinforces what the education act said all along that all 
handicapped children are entitled to an education 
they shouldnt have to fight to get in the schoolhouse door 
</TEXT>
