<TEXT>
spurred by criticism from asian 
americans the university of california at berkeley announced plans 
today to put more weight on academics in admissions and also open 
new spots for the poor 
the proposal adds the poor to the list of groups given special 
consideration said robert l bailey a member of the committee 
that drafted the proposals special consideration already is given 
on the basis of race ethnicity and other factors 
if approved by the administration the policy changes will take 
effect by the fall of 1991 
the changes were proposed in part because of complaints that 
current policies discriminate against asian american applicants 
changes in 198384 withdrew automatic admission for all 
academically eligible students who were also poor a program that 
had benefited many asian students said sociology professor and 
committee chairman jerome karabel 
the new proposal would restore that policy 
asian americans make up about 26 percent of berkeleys 
undergraduates in california 328 percent of asian high school 
graduates meet uc academic requirements compared with 158 percent 
of whites 5 percent of hispanics and 45 percent of blacks 
under the proposal the proportion of freshmen admitted on the 
basis of outstanding academic records alone would be raised from 40 
percent to 50 percent 
another 45 percent would be selected from among groups given 
special consideration whether on the basis of race ethnicity 
income or other factors these students would still have to meet uc 
academic standards 
the proposal also would reserve 5 percent of the freshman spaces 
for socioeconomically disadvantaged students including blacks 
hispanics indians athletes and the disabled reentry applicants 
typically older women would also get special consideration 
there will be more disadvantaged white and asian students on 
the campus karabel said the addition of the economic 
disadvantage category is in addition to affirmative action based 
on race not in place of it and will not lower the number of 
underrepresented minorities on campus he said 
the number of applicants to berkeley has increased dramatically 
since 1981 with more than 20000 people applying for 3400 
freshman slots each year 
