<TEXT>
the nations air traffic controllers complain 
they are handling too many planes working too many hours and 
suffering from low morale in a system that has changed little since 
the same problems were cited four years ago a congressional report 
said today 
in short the federal aviation administration simply 
ignored recommendations for change said rep guy v molinari 
rny referring to the general accounting office study that 
showed 43 percent of controllers characterize their morale as low 
faa officials said their own surveys painted a brighter picture 
the gao study said that while most controllers were concerned 
about working conditions the increasing traffic they have to 
handle and other aspects of air traffic control that affect 
system safety and operating efficiency their supervisors were 
far less concerned 
the survey released at a house subcommittee hearing was based 
on 5098 questionnnaires filled out by controllers and supervisors 
at the faas largest facilities late last year 
molinari ranking minority member of the public works and 
transportation subcommittee on investigations and oversight said 
the results were nearly a replica of a similar 1985 gao survey 
and show that many of the problems that contributed to a 1981 air 
traffic controllers strike still exist 
more than 11000 controllers were fired for the illegal walkout 
and molinari said the system still has 3600 fewer fully qualified 
controllers than it did before the strike the faa says the work 
force totals 16464 with 9689 classified as full performance 
controllers 
molinari said the number of full performance controllers has 
dropped by 150 in the last six months 
the faa has failed in these eight years to rebuild the air 
traffic control system adequately and they have failed to heed the 
views of controllers and supervisors he said 
gao official kenneth m mead said the flight safety foundation 
concluded from the survey that the system is not unsafe but that 
the margin of safety that undefined limit beyond which the system 
would no longer be safe remains less than desirable 
the private foundation acts as a consultant to the gao which is 
the investigative arm of congress 
