<TEXT>
the internal revenue service says farmers may 
be liable for capitalgains taxes if part of a farmers home 
administration loan is forgiven 
the ruling which was made public in a letter to members of 
congress is in line with the law affecting other taxpayers which 
holds generally that forgiveness of a debt creates taxable income 
we are disappointed but its not something that was totally 
unexpected jim sinner an aide to rep byron dorgan dnd 
said thursday what the irs is saying basically is that where 
there is forgiveness of debt there is going to be an income tax 
consequence 
the irs letter resulted from a farmers home administration query 
asking hypothetically how a restructuring of an fmha loan would be 
treated for tax purposes 
the one outstanding issue that was resolved in this irs 
explanation is treatment of sharedappreciation agreements and 
other contractual arrangements that continue beyond the act of 
restructuring sinner said 
under shared appreciation a farmer agrees that as a condition 
of having a loan restructured any increase in value of the 
property securing the loan over the next 10 years will be shared 
with the government 
under the ruling sinner said current taxes would not be 
affected by such an agreement but once the property increases in 
value and the sharing arrangement is triggered there would be a 
new calculation that takes into account the higher value 
sinner said dorgan will introduce a bill that would forgive 
taxes due on restructured loans in cases in which the farmer is 
operating on a margin so thin that he cannot afford the taxes 
