<TEXT>
regulators and consumer advocates urged 
congress thursday to open the way for quicker refunds to customers 
of more than 19 billion in excess taxes collected by utilities 
the plain unvarnished fact is that investorowned utilities 
have collected from ratepayers and are using for their own 
purposes 19 billion more about 223 per household than they 
owe the us government for income taxes susan c stone a 
member of the illinois commerce commission told a news conference 
the taxes were collected in advance from customers in 
anticipation that the utilities would have to pay federal taxes at 
a maximum corporate rate of 46 percent however that rate was 
reduced to 34 percent in 1986 and power companies and other 
utilities were allowed to keep the excess taxes for as long as 30 
years before refunding them 
a bill introduced by reps bob matsui dcalif and byron 
dorgan dnd would authorize state utility commissioners to 
require that the taxes be refunded to customers over a period of at 
least three years starting in 1991 
never before in my 11 years in congress has an issue been as 
crystal clear as this one matsui said its a matter of right 
vs wrong good public policy vs bad special interests ethics vs 
greed 
utilities insist they need to retain the taxes for much longer 
to finance improvement of plant and equipment 
this money is not just sitting in a bank account said bill 
mccloskey spokesman for bellsouth it is being used to improve 
the telephone network for the benefit of our customers which is 
the exact intention of the tax code 
david m barasch president of the national association of state 
utility consumer advocates said there is no disagreement that 
utilities will never have to pay the excess taxes over to the 
government the only issue he said is how soon the money should 
be returned to taxpayers 
the timing of refunds is a consumer protection and utility 
health issue that is within the expertise of regulators rather 
than tax collectors said peter bradford chairman of the new 
york state public service commission the bill he added 
corrects this glaring flaw by providing a minimum refund period 
that is more in line with economic reality 
