the government launched a campaign thursday to 
encourage parents to talk more explicitly with their children about 
sex saying their failure to do so has contributed to the aids 
epidemic 
the parent who does not take time today to teach his or her 
child properly could end up later in a hospital room watching that 
child die said dr james o mason assistant secretary of health 
and human services 
mason unveiled a 15 million campaign involving a new brochure 
and television advertisements designed to spur family dialogues 
about sex and aids 
he said the program is taking a somewhat different tack 
stressing the advantages of sexual abstinence by youth than 
earlier aidsprevention campaigns which put more emphasis on the 
use of condoms as a safe sex option 
kids and condoms dont work awfully well said mason 
weve done studies and we find that they act on impulse they 
dont plan ahead so a condom is there 
i think the fact that parents have not sat down and talked 
with their children is the reason that were today reaping the 
harvest of hiv human immunodeficiency virus which causes aids 
said mason were trying to bring the nations parents into this 
picture and let them make the contribution that they are capable 
of making 
mason also blamed the lack of frank parental guidance for 
contributing to other sexually transmitted diseases and the 1 
million teenage pregnancies annually 
