<TEXT>
top business economists predicted on thursday 
that the us economy is headed for a soft landing in which 
growth slows enough to tame inflation and interest rates without 
toppling the country into a recession this year 
the latest survey from the national association of business 
economists projects that the gross national product the broadest 
measure of the economys health will grow 28 percent this year 
and 18 percent in 1990 
that would represent a significant retreat from the robust 39 
percent pace of growth last year 
jay n woodworth president of the association and an economist 
with bankers trust co said the report supports the case for a 
soft landing to take place in the economy a period of fairly 
slow gnp growth slow enough so that it takes the pressure off the 
inflation rate it takes the pressure off interest rates 
the anticipated slowdown also is likely to be accompanied by an 
increase in unemployment and slower growth in industrial 
production the forecasters said 
while signs of a slowdown already have been emerging the 
quarterly surveys by the business group have been becoming 
gradually more optimistic about prospects for avoiding a recession 
fortythree percent of the 54 analysts surveyed earlier this 
month predicted the next recession would occur in 1990 while 20 
percent expect the nations record peacetime expansion to end this 
year 
that projection is slightly more optimistic than the groups 
last quarterly forecast issued in february when 75 percent of 
those surveyed expected a recession this year or next last 
november 88 percent expected a recession by the end of next year 
recent government reports measuring the economys performance so 
far this year indicate that growth is slowing in response to a 
federal reserve campaign to restrain economic growth and curb 
inflation by pushing up interest rates 
the government reported thursday that the gnp grew at a 43 
percent annual rate in the first three months of 1989 much slower 
than previously thought the pace was a lackluster 18 percent when 
a statistical bounceback from last years drought is excluded 
but woodworth said the new gnp report was good news because 
it reflects a downward revision in the accumulation of inventories 
held by businesses 
if the groups economists were polled again now they might be 
just a trace more optimistic than they were when surveyed earlier 
this month woodworth said 
despite their growing optimism the forecasters acknowledged 
that the real trick from an economic policy perspective is 
preventing the forces that are responsible for a major slowdown 
from degenerating into a fullblown recession 
soft landings have often appeared possible but inflation 
has invariably worsened the groups report said with the 
runup in prices government policy has been forced to squeeze 
still harder and soft landings are lost in the process 
the economists forecast that in conjunction with slower growth 
the unemployment rate will creep up from a 15year low of 5 percent 
in march averaging 54 percent for all of 1989 and 58 percent in 
1990 
inflation which advanced at a sharp 66 percent pace in the 
first four months of 1989 was expected to peak at the middle of 
the year and then moderate price increases were forecast to 
average 53 percent this year and 47 percent in 1990 up from 44 
percent in 1988 
both long and shortterm interest rates were expected to 
continue dropping with current declines in rates already 
outstripping the groups projections 
the yield on threemonth treasury bills was projected to drop 
from 88 percent in march to 73 percent in december 1990 yields 
on 30year treasury bonds were estimated at 87 percent in december 
1990 down from 92 percent this march 
progress on the countrys twin trade and budget deficits 
meanwhile was expected to continue over the next two years but at 
a slower pace 
the median trade deficit forecast was 112 billion for 1989 and 
100 billion in 1990 down from 1198 billion in 1988 the budget 
deficit which reached 1551 billion in 1988 was pegged at 160 
billion for 1989 and 140 billion in 1990 
