corporations aftertax profits fell 17 
percent in the first quarter of 1989 the biggest decline in more 
than a year the government said thursday 
in a report indicating earnings are slowing along with the 
economy the commerce department said aftertax profits dipped to a 
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1716 billion during the first 
quarter down from 1745 billion during the previous threemonth 
period 
decreases in profits were widespread within manufacturing 
industries while earnings in trade transportation public 
utilities and other nonmanufacturing industries also fell 
aftertax profits had risen 147 percent during 1988 reflecting 
the robust economic growth that occurred last year but earnings 
are widely expected to fade this year as the economy slows and 
labor costs rise 
economist allen sinai of the boston co called it a standard 
latestage business expansion phenomenon for earnings to fall as 
an economic recovery ages 
the firstquarter falloff in aftertax profits was the biggest 
drop since a 25 decline registered in the fourth quarter of 1987 
the momentum of growth in profits in the first quarter showed 
significant signs of beginning to fade and that will be the story 
on profits for the next year sinai predicted 
among the details in the profits report 
beforetax profits edged down 02 percent last quarter to a 
seasonally adjusted annual level of 3199 billion after rising 
21 percent during the previous threemonth period 
corporate profits after adjusting for depreciation and 
inventories fell 63 percent last quarter to a seasonally 
adjusted annual rate of 3193 billion after rising 33 percent in 
the fourth quarter 
corporate cash flows a measurement intended to show the funds 
corporations have for investment fell 53 percent last quarter to 
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3881 billion after rising 
34 percent during the fourth quarter 
dividend payments to stockholders rose 29 percent in the first 
quarter to an annual rate of 1111 billion following a 22 
percent rise in the fourth quarter 
