<TEXT>
consumer food prices are rising faster than 
predicted a few months ago and may gain an average of 5 percent to 
7 percent over the entire year the agriculture department said 
thursday 
that would compare with a 1988 average gain of 41 percent and 
would be the sharpest 12month increase since 1981 when retail 
food prices rose 79 percent 
consumer demand will pull up food prices in 1989 the 
departments economic research service said while growth in the 
general economy is slowing growth in real disposable personal 
income is still likely to be 2 percent to 3 percent this year 
after rising 29 percent last year 
the report said that the labor departments consumer price index 
for food increased at an annual rate of 86 percent in the first 
three months of 1989 well above the rate expected last fall 
additional upward adjustments are likely for the rest of this 
year based primarily on the strength of consumer demand and the 
impact of higher petroleum prices the report said 
much of the sharp rise in the first quarter was blamed on cold 
weather in mexico florida and california which cut supplies of 
fresh vegetables retail prices which had been expected to decline 
during the quarter rose an average of 57 percent 
other price increases in the first quarter resulted from 
lingering effects of last summers drought 
processed vegetable prices continued to rise because of 
smaller supplies of canned sweet corn green peas snap beans and 
dry beans all victims of the drought the report said smaller 
supplies of canned vegetables forced frozen vegetable prices higher 
as well 
another firstquarter factor was retail egg prices up 295 
percent from a year earlier production was cut back because of 
high droughtrelated feed costs the report said 
food price increases are expected to be more moderate in the 
remainder of 1989 prices for meats poultry and fish will remain 
reasonably stable for the rest of the year the report said egg 
prices are expected to fluctuate but should remain well above 
yearearlier levels 
retail prices of fresh vegetables following a normal pattern 
will decline this spring and summer from the first quarters high 
marks and then ease up again in the fourth quarter 
prices of cereals and bakery products fats and oils and other 
prepared foods were forecast to rise at a modest but steady 1 
percent to 3 percent annual rate per quarter through 1989 
</TEXT>
