<TEXT>
two environmental groups joined the state of 
california and the aflcio on thursday in suing the environmental 
protection agency for allegedly failing to protect consumers from 
dangerous pesticides in food 
the suit asks that the federal courts require the epa to impose 
more stringent regulations on cancercausing chemicals in food 
especially in processed fruits and vegetables often consumed by 
small children 
al meyerhoff an attorney for the natural resources defense 
council said the suit is aimed at forcing the epa to be more 
aggressive in prohibiting the use of pesticides on food and to ban 
them altogether if they are found to cause cancer 
under current epa procedures the agency allows the use of some 
older pesticides even though agency officials concede that if the 
same chemicals were newly introduced they would not be approved 
because of health concerns 
the agency is in the midst of reexamining scores of older 
pesticides using current health criteria but that process could 
take years 
at the same time the agency applies a negligible risk test 
when determining whether a cancercausing chemical should continue 
to be used banning it if the increased risk is one in one million 
the suit asks the court to direct the epa to automatically take a 
chemical off the market for food use if there is any proof it is 
carcinogenic no matter what the expected risk 
the suit filed in us district court in sacramento calif 
accused the epa of a consistent failure to carry out the 
requirements of the food drug and cosmetic act which requires the 
regulation of unsafe residues from pesticides on food products 
the epa had no comment on the suit 
jay vroom executive vice president of the national agricultural 
chemicals association criticized the suit as a political move 
for additional publicity to further confuse and confound the 
public about the dangers of pesticides in food 
the industry has consistently argued that the levels of 
pesticides in food products is so low as to pose no health danger 
in addition to the natural resources defense council plaintiffs 
in the lawsuit are public citizen a private environmetnal and 
consumer group in washington the state attorney general of 
california and the aflcio the nrdc is a private nonprofit 
environmental organization 
the suit also charges the epa with not requiring enough 
information from processsed food manufacturers to determine residue 
levels of many pesticides including some that have been found to 
cause cancer 
the law requires epa to identify cancercausing pesticides in 
processed foods by refusing to collect the data and to apply 
the law epa jeopardizes the public health and violates the public 
trust said william schultz an attorney for public citizen a 
private environmental and consumer group 
in addition to the suit the plaintiffs filed a petition with 
the epa asking that seven cancercausing pesticides immediately be 
banned in processed foods they argued such a ban is required under 
a 1958 law although the chemicals were in use prior to that 
these pesticides have been found to have higher concentrations 
of residues in processed foods than in raw agricultural products 
the petition maintains and should be subject to a provision of the 
1958 law that prohibits any levels of a carcinogenic pesticide in 
certain foods 
the epa has said that the socalled delaney clause in the 1958 
law does not apply to pesticides that were approved for use prior 
to the laws enactment even though latest tests showed them to be 
carcinogenic in such cases the agency allowed if they are 
perceived to pose merely a negligible risk 
the plaintiffs claim there are at leat 20 pesticides now allowed 
by the epa in processed foods despite links of various degrees to 
cancer 
</TEXT>
