<DOCNO> AP890525-0190 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
fouryearolds who were able to wait the 
longest in preschool for rewards of candy treats tend later in 
life to accomplish more to be more intelligent and to have higher 
scores on college entrance exams researchers said thursday 
thats the finding of three columbia university researchers who 
followed up on experiments conducted in the 1970s among students at 
a stanford university preschool the study is to be published 
friday in the journal science 
columbia researchers walter mischel yuichi shoda and monica l 
rodriguez reported in the study that children who tend to prefer 
delayed rewards tend to be more intelligent more likely to 
resist temptation to have greater social responsibility and higher 
achievement strivings 
and when those children later took scholastic aptitude tests for 
college the coauthors said the patience they demonstrated in 
preschool is reflected in higher scores and better academic 
performance 
the early studies at stanford involved teaching preschoolers a 
game in which they were shown a pair of treats of different value 
prior to being left alone in a room the first treat for instance 
could be one marshmallow and the more valuable treat could be two 
marshmallows 
each child was told that they could receive the more valuable 
treat by waiting until the experimenter returned to the room 
the wait could be ended at any time by ringing a bell but this 
would result in the least valuable of the treats in effect the 
rule was the longer they waited the more they got 
after a child was left alone the researchers recorded the 
length of the delay and observed the child without being seen 
typically the child was left alone for about 15 minutes unless 
the child ended the wait himself 
a recent followup said the researchers showed that those 
who had waited longer in this situation at 4 years of age were 
described more than 10 years later by their parents as adolescents 
who were more academically and socially competent than their peers 
and more able to cope with frustration and resist temptation 
at least 35 of the children tested in the 1970s in one variation 
of the experiment have since taken sat examinations for college 
admission and the researchers said their verbal and 
quantititative sat scores were significantly related to seconds of 
preschool delay time 
the more seconds that a child was able to wait while a 
preschooler the study said the higher the child later scored on 
the sat tests 
since there was only a small sample in the group that has taken 
sat exams the columbia researchers said that the finding 
dictates special caution they said more research is needed to 
establish the relationship between learning at an early age to 
delay gratification and the later effects in life 
science which published the study is a the journal of the 
american association for the advancement of science 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
