<DOCNO> AP890525-0207 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
aids patients with a form of pneumonia commonly 
fatal to them are more than three times as likely to survive in 
hospitals experienced in treating aids sufferers than in other 
hospitals a study suggests 
the findings support the belief that regional centers are needed 
to provide the best care for people with the aids virus said 
authors of the study published in fridays journal of the american 
medical association 
the study involved 257 aids patients with the infection called 
pneumocystis carinii pneumonia it found that the inhospital death 
rate was only 12 percent at experienced hospitals compared with 33 
percent at hospitals less familiar with aids 
after making statistical adjustments to correct for differences 
in severity of illness the inhospital death rate for aids 
patients with the pneumonia was about 36 times higher than in less 
experienced hospitals the study said 
researchers said they studied patients with the pneumonia 
because it is a common complication of aids often treated 
successfully but frequently leading to death 
hospitals considered experienced in the study were those that 
discharged at least 30 patients with aidsrelated medical problems 
for every 10000 patients discharged overall 
all patients studied were at 15 california hospitals 
researchers said 
it is likely that the technology for fighting aids is being 
developed unevenly among the nations hospitals and that 
hospitals with low aids familiarity are at a marked disadvantage in 
the treatment of patients with aids said the researchers led by 
dr charles l bennett of the randuniversity of california at los 
angeles center for health policy study and the ucla school of 
medicine 
creating regional aids centers soon would be a tough job 
according to an accompanying jama editorial in which dr deborah j 
cotton of beth israel hospital in boston said the nations health 
care system is already in crisis 
problems would include how to meet the patients needs for 
longterm care and community services outside the centers and the 
possibility that special hospitals might increase the isolation 
and stigmatization experienced by patients with aids 
nonetheless the creation of such centers should be considered 
urgently as part of alongterm planning strategies she wrote 
as aids therapy becomes more complex the ability of many 
acutecare hospitals to provide such therapy will become 
increasingly difficult 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

