he was bound by its decision to support gorbachev only 14 deputies 
opposed a motion not to put his name on the ballot 
with the exception of the secret ballot the entire session was 
televised live offering soviets a rare look at the workings of 
their government still the soviets lack of experience with 
parliamentary democracy was apparent 
gorbachev as presiding officer arbitrarily called for votes on 
some procedural issues while ignoring others only a few deputies 
objected 
there was fierce debate over procedural issues but the agenda 
hammered out in advance by gorbachev and a few hundred deputies in 
a private caucus wednesday was adopted by a lopsided margin 
sakharov and economist gavril popov led the fight against the 
establishment 
sakharov once the nations most famed dissident and now a 
member of the parliament praised gorbachev 
i dont see another person who could lead the country at this 
time said the winner of the 1975 nobel peace prize but he added 
gorbachev should first be required to give an account of the 
mistakes and achievements of his reform program 
gorbachev a giant statue of vladimir i lenin at his back 
frequently intervened in the debate amid shouts from the floor 
guiding and controlling the assembly in the vast auditorium of the 
kremlins marbleandglass palace of congresses 
