<TEXT>
a new ethnic studies requirement at the 
university of california at berkeley that includes the study of 
european americans is being heralded by supporters as an important 
step in improving campus curriculum 
opponents call it the hula hoop of the 80s something that 
creates great excitement at the moment but will likely be soon 
forgotten 
i think its the most significant requirement of its kind to 
be adopted at any university that i know of because its based upon 
the multicultural heritage of this country said history 
professor lawrence levine 
it sends a signal to schools nationwide that it is important to 
examine the ethnic groups that are part of the formula that 
created america said levine a member of the faculty committee 
that drafted the proposal 
faculty members recently approved the american cultures 
requirement beginning in 1991 freshmen and sophomores will have 
to take a course on race culture and ethnicity in american history 
and society entering juniors or seniors beginning in fall 1993 
also will have to meet the requirement 
the plan calls for study of three of five major cultural groups 
african americans american indians asian americans 
chicanolatinos and european americans 
when a similar proposal without the european american element 
reached the academic senate in may 1988 a shouting match erupted 
and the measure was ultimately sent back to a faculty committee 
but the compromise addition of europeans did not diminish all 
opposition only 20 percent of eligible faculty voted on the final 
measure and some supporters took the turnout as a distressing sign 
of apathy 
i think it was a very bad idea but the political pressure was 
very strong to pass it said hans sluga a philosophy professor 
who opposed the proposal and boycotted the vote to oppose political 
pressure to approve the requirement he called the idea the hula 
hoop of the 80s 
sluga favored a free market approach to education that 
allows students to choose their own courses he also criticized the 
requirement as too narrowly defined because it focuses on cultural 
groups inside the united states 
you could study chinese in chinatown but not in china he 
complained 
the intent is to incorporate voices that have been left out of 
american history institutions music and literature said 
student body president jeff chang who helped coordinate students 
lobbying the faculty 
nearly half the 22671 undergraduates at berkeleye are white 
slightly more than onefourth are asian about 11 percent are 
hispanic and 7 percent black 
advocates agreed that the test of the requirement will be in its 
implementation and barbara christian a professor in the 
afroamerican studies department acknowledged it will be a 
challenge to teach the courses 
the question is whether or not we will be able to do the 
necessary work to know the different groups i think we as a 
faculty are going to have to learn a great deal and there will 
probably be team teaching as a result 
proposals include an architecture class to study ethnic 
neighborhoods and a linguistics class to study ethnic dialects and 
bilingualism 
schools across the country are debating plans designed to 
highlight the contributions of minorities and women 
last year stanford university replaced its freshman western 
culture requirement with a new course that rejected many classic 
works in favor of books by feminists minority leaders and social 
revolutionaries 
other university of california campuses including santa barbara 
and davis are considering mandatory ethnic studies classes and 
irvine has approved required courses in multicultural studies and 
international affairs 
at berkeley some opponents argued that the course is 
unnecessary while others said the campus lacks the needed 
classroom space 
although ucberkeley chancellor ira michael heyman who strongly 
supported the requirement assured faculty members that the campus 
longterm expansion plans include adequate facilities critics 
dismissed the promise 
leaders of some minority student groups said the amendment to 
include european americans undermined the intent of the requirement 
weve learned it all our lives said emily ihara chairwoman 
of the asian student union i felt like we didnt need to learn 
more about it in this class the whole point is to make up 
sometimes for what happens in the classroom 
other supporters said they bowed to political reality when they 
endorsed the revised requirement 
we felt we can live with that for the larger purpose of 
getting the requirement explained guillermo rodriguez the lone 
student member on the uc regents and an advocate who worked on the 
proposal for three years there is also a need to understand some 
of the cultures of nonminority or nonthird world people 
rodriguez 21 a junior majoring in sociology countered 
assertions that the requirement is largely symbolic i think its 
moving in the right direction i think if it opens one mind thats 
one mind opened and thats good enough 
