<TEXT>
pope john paul ii is coming to 
scandinavia where roman catholicism vanquished by the protestant 
reformation was proscribed for more than 300 years until a century 
ago 
the pope will spend 10 days in norway iceland finland denmark 
and sweden starting june 1 
overwhelmingly secular and affluent scandinavians especially 
the young show little patience with traditional moral standards 
attitudes toward sex are liberal and marriage is optional in 
sweden for example the statistics bureau said last year that some 
50 percent of all couples living together dont bother to exchange 
vows the figure is higher in iceland 
couples who register as cohabitants have virtually the same 
legal rights as do man and wife 
in sweden and denmark homosexual couples have equal rights 
birth control is encouraged abortions occur at a rate of about 
20 per 1000 women while slightly lower in finland an abortion is 
available without questions to any woman above the age of consent 
up to the 12th week of pregnancy 
in the era of aids condoms are distributed in many schools and 
advertised on billboards 
we are in a helpless situation said ake goransson director 
of studies for the roman catholic diocese in sweden 
we have many catholics who dont marry not because they are 
afraid they wont be able to divorce but because marriage is just 
not common in sweden 
swedish catholics a community of 135000 had only 260 
marriages last year 
the scandinavian dioceses run education classes usually on 
saturdays to teach the vaticans position on such questions as the 
sanctity of marriage and the purpose of sex 
we have a broad program of christian education for our kids so 
they can make their own decisions said goransson the church 
doesnt want to tell catholics what to do you must follow your own 
conscience but your conscience must be taught 
the pope was expected to speak on issues of mans faithfulness 
to god and to each other and parental responsibility said 
goransson 
to one degree or another the lutheran church is an arm of the 
state in all five countries about 90 percent of the populations 
belong to the official taxsupported churches 
membership in the state church is automatic for anyone born of 
lutheran parents clergymen are civil servants paid by the state 
and bishops are appointed by government 
but religion plays little role 
in sweden about 10 percent say they are regular churchgoers in 
norway cities are virtually shut down for the easter holiday while 
norwegians go skiing 
some say christianity never really took root when it came to the 
viking cultures 1000 years ago 
the benedictine monk ansgar brought christianity to denmark and 
sweden in the 9th century but it took two centuries to spread 
throughout scandinavia 
danish chroniclers say a monk called poppo convinced king harald 
bluetooth of christianitys power by carrying a redhot iron in his 
hands in the year 960 
the roman church came to finland by way of an englishled 
crusade in 1155 it vied with the orthodox church from russia 
which still has a strong foothold 
the 16thcentury protestant reformation was the tool for the 
scandinavian kings to seize church property and the wealth of what 
had become a powerful force in sweden the church owned onefifth 
of all farms 
for one brief period in denmark being catholic was a capital 
offense 
freedom of religion was restored throughout the region in the 
19th century and today catholics are a small but growing minority 
a liberal policy toward refugees in sweden norway and denmark 
has brought catholics mostly from chile in the last several years 
thousands also came from poland after the labor unrest that began 
