<TEXT>
limits on steel imports have helped change the 
fortunes of us steel producers but industry executives say 
nothing has changed about the way other nations behave in 
international trade 
there is no fair trade in steel especially among the 29 
countries currently operating under the voluntary restraint 
agreements bethlehem steel corp chairman walter f williams 
said wednesday each and every one of them is currently trading 
unfairly in the us 
we have the documentation to prove it he said at the annual 
conference of the american iron and steel institute 
domestic producers are prepared to file trade lawsuits against 
virtually all of the united states trading partners without an 
extension of the fiveyear vra program williams said 
president bush is expected to fulfill a campaign promise to 
extend quotas past their sept 30 expiration but steel executives 
are concerned he may impose the second round of vras for less than 
five years or otherwise weaken the restraints 
after a slow start in october 1984 the vras are now limiting 
imports to around 20 percent of the us market 
the us producers said no nation should be allowed to ship 
steel to the united states without restriction as australia 
mexico and korea have requested 
even canada should be included they said although most steel 
producers seem to be trying to abide by an understanding that 
canada will claim no more than 25 percent of the us market 
political realities make it unlikely bush will demand a quota 
agreement from canada the united states largest trading partner 
said thomas c graham outgoing aisi chairman and president of usx 
corps steel division the largest us steelmaker 
williams cited examples of alleged illegal trade practices 
italy is bailing out their stateowned steel company for the 
third or fourth time frankly ive lost track to the tune of about 
another 4 billion he said 
indonesia plans to give 425 million to save a steel rolling 
mill that is partially government owned imports of indonesian 
steel are not restricted and shipments have risen from virtually 
nothing several years ago to 265000 tons in 1988 
theyre planning to triple their steel exports over the next 
decade williams said 
acesita a governmentowned specialty steel producer in brazil 
is negotiating for a 70 percent expansion in its production 
capacity primarily for export williams said brazilian steel 
capacity already far exceeds domestic needs 
us producers suspect the australian government cut a deal 
with its steelmakers in exchange for private investment in steel 
plants the government would shield the domestic market from imports 
and pay bounties to australian steel consumers for the spread 
between the higher domestic and lower foreign price 
our information is that the australian government starting in 
1984 has paid out up to 64 million a year in these bounties 
williams said 
and british steel has been privatized as of last fall and now 
declares itself debt free and ready to take on all comers after 
their government converted 12 billion of debt into 4 billion of 
equity for an estimated 8 billion loss he said 
last year canada shipped 32 million tons of steel to the 
united states brazil 137 million tons south korea 13 million 
tons france 124 million tons mexico 471200 tons italy 
326200 tons and australia 282000 tons 
steel importers say the us government also subsidized steel 
production through unemployment compensation to laid off workers 
and in defaulted loans 
but us companies say such financial support pales by 
comparison to foreign government ownership and investment in steel 
production 
