<TEXT>
three former first jersey securities brokers 
have been indicted in an alleged 1 million money laundering scheme 
the brokers working out of the firms paterson and cherry hill 
offices allegedly hid from the internal revenue service money that 
was given to them by brokerage customers us attorney samuel a 
alito jr said 
in two indictments returned wednesday by a federal grand jury 
the former brokers also were charged with conspiring to defraud the 
irs by preventing the brokerage firm from reporting large cash 
payments alito said 
indicted were kevin odonohue 31 of cherry hill arthur 
basmajian 30 of pittsburgh formerly of cherry hill and dominic 
padula 46 of paterson 
if convicted odonohue faces up to 35 years in prison padula 
faces up to 20 years in prison and basmajian faces up to 15 years 
in prison alito said they all could face fines of 500000 alito 
said 
he said basmajian and odonohue were brokers at the cherry hill 
office and padula worked at the paterson branch 
under irs regulations cash transactions of more than 10000 
were required to be reported to the irs on a form identifying the 
person making the payment 
the irs uses the information to reveal various illegal 
activities including drug transactions and tax evasion alito said 
the indicted brokers allegedly helped customers conceal the cash 
from the irs by having first jersey employees convert cash deposits 
into cashiers checks at local banks in amounts less than 10000 
those checks were then returned to the brokerage and deposited into 
the customers accounts according to the indictment 
alito said all the men are expected to receive summonses and be 
arraigned within 10 days he said there were no plans to indict the 
customers but he added the investigation is continuing 
simply by handling an account of this nature a broker can 
earn commission as the customer buys and sells stocks he said 
all three of those indicted specifically are charged with 
conspiracy in addition odonohue is charged with six counts of 
money laundering basmajian is charged with two counts of money 
laundering and padula is charged with three counts of money 
laundering 
