<TEXT>
a modest 27 percent rise in midmay car and 
light truck sales may indicate a softerthanexpected market and 
force two of the big three automakers to extend incentive programs 
analysts say 
the eight major automakers assembling vehicles in north america 
reported wednesday they sold cars and light trucks at an average 
daily rate of 39360 from may 1120 compared with 38334 in the 
same 1988 period 
analysts expected an increase mainly because many incentives 
expired may 11 last year customers planning to buy cars in mid or 
latemay 1988 made their purchases early to take advantage of the 
deals which reduced sales in the period 
i dont know what its going to take to bring customers back 
to the showrooms said analyst mary anne sudol of fitch investors 
service inc in new york i think demand is just tired at this 
point 
general motors corp ford motor co chrysler corp and some 
overseas automakers had wideranging incentive plans in effect this 
month to lure people into showrooms 
but demand may not be there said tom webb a senior economist 
with the national automobile dealers association in mclean va 
basically what sales have shown is that the underlying demand 
is less than what most people expected he said given those 
sales theres going to have to be some further production cuts 
they would be modest though 
automakers often trim their inventories through incentives and 
production cuts 
speculation that ford and gm need to continue incentives past 
their expiration dates during the next two weeks grew with 
wednesdays sales reports said webb theres no doubt about 
that 
ford spokesman bill carroll said he expected another more 
limited incentive package to be announced may 31 when the 
companys current program expires 
most of gms program ends june 5 but on wednesday the 
corporations pontiac division announced a wider selection of cars 
qualifying for cash rebates or lowinterest financing gm also 
boosted the cash offer on a few pontiac cars 
chryslers program continues indefinitely 
the incentive programs were prompted by slowerthananticipated 
sales during the first three months of the year 
since new years day car and truck sales by the eight makers 
were running 36 percent behind the pace for 1988 the secondbest 
year in automotive history car sales were running 54 percent 
behind and truck sales were down 03 percent 
ford sold cars at an average daily rate of 7616 during the may 
period compared with 7410 last year a 28 percent increase car 
sales so far this year were 05 percent behind last year 
