<TEXT>
a federal court ruling that upheld the 
constitutionality of wisconsins antitakeover law was a victory 
for universal foods corp in its fight against a hostile 
acquisition bid 
attorneys were notified wednesday that the law which prevents 
successful bidders from swiftly selling newly acquired assets was 
upheld by the 7th circuit court of appeals in chicago 
the law had been challenged by high voltage engineering corp a 
company owned by new york investors who began a campaign last year 
to buy a controlling share of universal stock 
in a 21page decision judge frank h easterbrook said 
wisconsins law may well be folly we are confident that it is 
constitutional 
clifford press deputy chairman of high voltage said his 
company would review its options in light of the ruling 
the court found that although the statute may well be economic 
folly it is constitutional press said while not deciding the 
poisonpill case the opinion does cast serious doubt on 
universals justsayno defense in light of the court decision 
we are reviewing our options 
the legislature enacted the law to help wisconsin companies ward 
off hostile takeovers easterbrook said it requires a successful 
bidder to wait three years before completing a merger or acquiring 
more than 5 percent of the wisconsin companys assets unless the 
company has agreed to the deal 
as a practical matter wisconsin prohibits any offer 
contingent on a merger between bidder and target a condition 
attached to about 90 percent of contemporary tender offers he 
said 
easterbrook said he and judges william j bauer and hubert l 
will questioned whether the law is fair to shareholders because 
tender offers are a way for investors to bypass company management 
the prospect of takeover induces managers to run corporations 
more efficiently he said 
skepticism about the wisdom of a states law does not lead to 
the conclusion that the law is beyond the states power however 
he said unless a federal statute or the constitution bars the 
way wisconsins choice must be respected 
universal presidernt guy a osborn who has urged shareholders 
not to accept the high voltage offer said his attorneys told him 
that we are the first company in more than four years that has 
been successful in staying independent 
high voltage had offered to buy universal stock at 38 a share 
a deal valued at about 750 million 
the law was previously upheld march 18 by judge joseph p 
stadtmueler of us district court in milwaukee 
</TEXT>
