<TEXT>
top business economists today predicted that 
economic growth will slow dramatically this year but the nation 
should be able to forestall a recession until at least 1990 
the consensus of 54 forecasting experts surveyed by the national 
association of business economists was that america will experience 
a growth recession in which the economy continues to expand 
but at a very slow pace 
the slowdown is expected to be accompanied by a moderate 
increase in unemployment and higher inflation due to an emerging 
upturn in food and energy prices according to the associations 
latest quarterly survey 
1990 continues to be the year economists predict a recession 
will arrive fortythree percent predict a downturn then while 20 
percent expect record peacetime expansion to end this year 
that projection is slightly more optimistic than the groups 
last quarterly forecast issued in february when 75 percent of 
those surveyed expected a recession this year or next 
in todays survey 17 percent forecast a recession for 1991 and 
20 percent said it would be 1992 or beyond before a downturn occurs 
recent government reports measuring the economys performance so 
far this year have suggested that growth is slowing in response to 
a federal reserve campaign to engineer a socalled soft 
landing in which the economy slows enough to cool inflation 
without slipping into a recession 
but the forecasters warned that the real trick from an 
economic policy perspective is preventing the forces that are 
responsible for a major slowdown from degenerating into a fullblown 
recession 
soft landings have often appeared possible but inflation 
has invariably worsened the group said in a summary of its 
findings with the runup in prices government policy has been 
forced to squeeze still harder and soft landings are lost in the 
process 
the analysts median forecast was that the gross national 
product the broadest measure of the economys health would grow 
at an sluggish annual rate of 13 percent during the final three 
quarters of 1989 
for the year overall the gnp was forecast to grow 28 percent 
down from 39 percent in 1988 growth was expected to slow even 
further in 1990 dropping to 18 percent 
that prognosis is considerably more pessimistic than the bush 
administration which is pinning its budget and deficitreduction 
plans on gnp growth of 32 percent this year and next 
the government reported today that the gnp grew at a 43 percent 
annual rate in the first three months of 1989 much slower than 
previously thought the pace was a lackluster 18 percent when a 
statistical bounceback from last years drought is excluded 
jay n woodworth president of the business economists group 
said the new gnp report reflects a downward revision in the amount 
of inventories held by businesses which bodes well for the economy 
woodworth said that were the groups economists polled today 
they might be just a trace more optimistic than they were when 
the survey was conducted earlier this month 
the overall slowing of the growth predicted in the forecasters 
survey was expected to reflect a sharp slackening in key sectors of 
the economy 
growth in industrial production was forecast at 32 percent in 
1989 and 18 percent in 1990 down from 57 percent last year 
construction of new homes and apartments was projected at 141 
million units in 1989 and 144 million in 1990 compared with 149 
in 1988 
car and truck sales were forecast to slip to 149 million for 
this year and next down from 159 million in 1988 
the economists also forecast that the slowdown in economic 
growth would be accompanied by an increase in the unemployment rate 
from a 15year low of 5 percent in march averaging 54 percent for 
all of 1989 and 58 percent in 1990 
inflation which advanced at a sharp 66 percent pace in the 
first four months of 1989 was expected to peak midyear and then 
become more moderate price increases were forecast to average 53 
this year and 47 percent in 1990 up from 44 percent in 1988 
progress on the countrys twin trade and budget deficits 
meanwhile was expected to continue over the next two years but at 
a slower pace 
the median trade deficit forecast was 112 billion for 1989 and 
100 billion in 1990 down from 1198 billion in 1988 the slower 
pace of improvement was linked to expectations of a drop in net 
exports from 991 billion in 1988 to 90 billion this year and 76 
billion in 1990 
the budget deficit which reached 1551 billion in 1988 was 
pegged at 160 billion for 1989 and 140 billion in 1990 that 
would exceed the grammrudman deficit reduction targets of 136 
billion and 100 billion for this year and next respectively 
the economic slowdown also was evident in the economists 
forecast for personal consumption expenditures which account for 
twothirds of overall economic activity consumer spending was 
expected to grow by 25 percent this year and 19 percent in 1990 
down from 28 percent in 1988 
</TEXT>
