lin broadcasting corp which has interests in 
television cellular telephone service and publishing said 
thursday its board has approved in principle spinning off its seven 
tv stations as a separate company 
the company a frequent subject of takeover speculation said 
the spinoff would be for operating purposes aimed at maximum 
development of the companys two principal businesses each of 
which will operate as an independent publiclyheld company 
it is not intended as a precursor to any other corporate 
transaction the company said 
but wall streeters pushed the companys stock sharply higher in 
the wake of the news lin stock rose 475 a share to 101 in 
consolidated national overthecounter trading 
the television stations and the cellular and publishing 
businesses have been roughly equal contributors to lins recent 
financial performance 
but analysts have said the companys cellular telephone business 
has proven increasingly attractive as that flegdling industry has 
expanded rapidly 
under the proposal backed by the board lin said stock of a new 
company that will own the seven lin tv stations would be spun off 
in a taxfree transaction to the holders of lins 51 million shares 
of stock 
each of the seven stations is affiliated with one of the three 
major networks 
lin would continue to own interests in five cellular telephone 
systems and a business that publishes specialty magazines for 
hotels 
the announcement said the details of the spinoff such as the 
exchange ratio and management structure of the new company not been 
determined 
but it said donald a pels chairman and chief executive of lin 
probably would be chief executive of lin and the new company 
pels said he anticipated the spinoff could be completed duirng 
the summer although he added he could offer no assurance the deal 
would be completed in that time period if at all 
in 1988 lins operating cash flow from its television stations 
amounted to 75 million on revenue of 137 million its cellular 
and publishing businesses had operating cash flow of 70 million on 
revenue of 142 million 
overall lin earned 821 million or 154 a share on revenue 
of 225 million in 1988 
its television stations include kxas in dallasfort worth wish 
in indianapolis wotv in grand rapidskalamazoobattle creek 
mich wavy in hampton roads va kxan in austin texas wand in 
decaturchampaignspringfielddanville ill and wane in fort 
wayne ind 
the companys cellular telelphone systems are in new york 
philadelphia los angeles dallasfort worth and houston 
its publishing unit creates advertisersupported hardcover 
magazines that are placed in the rooms of hotels in 37 metropolitan 
areas and provide guests with information about local attractions 
