<TEXT>
the bush administrations hit list of unfair 
trading practices leaves autos off the list of products improperly 
excluded from the japanese market auto industry and congressional 
offices said thursday 
the automotive issue however will be raised later in 
negotiations with tokyo on trade barriers built into the japanese 
regulatory and marketing system officials said 
the list was drawn up as part of a provision in a trade bill 
passed last year allowing the government to name countries whose 
trade barriers are most harmful to us producers 
chrysler corp the nations third largest automaker said we 
are very encouraged that the administration has included 
distribution systems in japan on its list of structural practices 
which are key parts of the ongoing trade imbalance 
chrysler will over the next 12 months aggressively attempt 
to fulfill its commitment to break into the japanese market as we 
have in europe and taiwan the company said 
the list named japan india and brazil as nations with 
restrictive trade barriers 
the list of harmful trade practices in japan named satellites 
supercomputers and forest products as areas that had suffered from 
japanese trading practices and omitted the automotive sector which 
accounts for almost twothirds of the 55 billion us trade 
imbalance with japan 
the law requires the administration to identify the most harmful 
trade barriers and gives it 18 months to negotiate removal of the 
barriers 
if the talks fail to produce results the government can levy 
tariffs of up to 100 percent against selected imports from an 
offending country 
automobiles and automotive parts are not on the formal list and 
so would not come under the 18month rule 
the negotiations on structural barriers dont list automotive 
issues specifically but aides to sen donald riegle dmich said 
automotive issues would be addressed in trade negotiations with 
japan 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0288 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the bush administration announced thursday 
that it had targeted trade barriers in japan brazil and india to 
meet a new us trade law a move that could mean huge tariffs 
against some foreign products 
the longawaited decision was announced by us trade 
representative carla hills 
she said the administration was citing japan for its refusal to 
buy us made satellites and supercomputers as well as its barriers 
on us lumber products 
mrs hills said the administration will immediately begin 
negotiations with the three countries to try to get the barriers 
removed so that any threatened us trade sanctions would be 
unnecessary 
while many foreign nations have bitterly attacked the onesided 
nature of the new us law mrs hills said she hopes all countries 
will understand that america is interested in opening markets 
rather than erecting trade barriers in this country 
this exercise is not intended to be offensive it is intended 
to carry out the law congress passed last year and we in the 
administration are sworn to uphold she told a packed news 
conference 
the 1988 omnibus trade act requires the administration to issue 
a sort of hit list identifying the trade barriers most harmful to 
american producers once that is done it has 18 months to 
negotiate the removal of the barriers if the talks are 
unsuccessful the government can levy tariffs of up to 100 percent 
against selected imports from an offending country 
officials said india would be cited for its restrictions on 
foreign investment and foreign insurance companies while brazil 
would be cited for its importlicensing practices 
the target countries and key congressional leaders were informed 
of the actions several hours before mrs hills news conference 
sen max baucus dmont and chairman of the senate finance 
subcommittee on international trade said he was pleased with the 
administrations initial response to the requirements in the trade 
law 
i think the administration deserves a passing grade they are 
stepping up to the problem baucus said this is a good start 
sen john danforth rmo called the action a very positive 
first step in utilizing a process which i hope will lead to more 
open world markets 
but there were critics rep dick gephardt dmo the author of 
an even tougher trade sanctions provision which was ultimately 
rejected by congress last year said bushs action was too timid 
and the administration had missed a golden opportunity to stand 
up for american workers and businesses 
nobuo matsunaga the japanese ambassador to the united states 
called the decision extremely regrettable and said any 
sanctions would be strongly opposed by his government 
in light of the good faith efforts that have been made the 
government of japan and the japanese people are greatly 
disappointed by this onesided decision matsunaga said in a 
statement there may well be some domestic backlash in japan 
which will make the resolution of the various problems even more 
difficult 
in addition to listing japan india and brazil for priority 
negotiations for flagrant trade barriers the administration put 
eight countries on a watch list because of their failure to 
provide protection for us patents and copyrights 
the eight countries placed on the watch list were brazil india 
mexico china south korea saudi arabia taiwan and thailand 
according to a fact sheet distributed to members of congress 
another 17 countries were cited as deserving special 
attention on the issue of copyright and patent protection with 
the administration promising to review progress in negotiations by 
nov 1 
those nations are argentina canada chile colombia egypt 
greece indonesia italy japan malaysia pakistan the 
philippines portugal spain turkey venezuela and yugoslavia 
however by citing no country as a priority violator of 
copyrights and patents the administration avoided triggering the 
strict timetables leading to possible sanctions 
in addition to naming japan as a priorty trade violator in three 
trade areas the administration also planned to begin negotiations 
with tokyo on socalled structural rigidities within japan which 
impede us sales baucus said 
the trade hit list has stirred anger among us allies who 
charge that the unilateral listing by the united states of a 
particular nation as an unfair trader violates the general 
agreement on tariffs and trade the pact which governs world trade 
some nations mounted extensive lobbying efforts to keep from 
being named to the list 
that lobbying effort worked for south korea taiwan and the 
12nation european community which were kept off despite having 
large trade surpluses with the united states 
congressional supporters of the new trade provision known as 
super 301 mounted their own campaign to make sure the 
administration named japan as a priority nation 
japan ran up a trade deficit with the united states of 52 
billion last year accounting for 44 percent of the total deficit 
of 1198 billion making it a prime target for inclusion on the 
trade list 
while south koreas deficit of 89 billion was among the 
largest of any nation officials from that country had stepped up 
efforts in the past weeks to reach agreements on the removal of 
various barriers against us products and the administration 
apparently took these concessions into account in making its 
determination 
the super 301 issue caused a deep split within bushs cabinet 
hills and commerce secretary robert mosbacher had urged an 
aggressive approach to carrying out the law saying failure to name 
several countries as flagrant trade violators risked a 
protectionist backlash in congress 
however michael boskin the presidents chief economic adviser 
and budget director richard darman countered that targeting japan 
americas closest ally in the pacific would be harmful to broader 
us interests 
the dispute went public earlier this month when boskin said in 
an appearance before a business group that us efforts to 
retaliate against its trading partners could spark a trade war and 
lead to a worldwide recession 
up until a decision made by president bush there was 
uncertainty over whether priority nations would be named or 
simply priority trade practices which would carry a lesser sting 
however those urging the naming of priority countries prevailed 
with bush 
rep ron wyden doregon said the administration acted only 
after heavy congressional pressure and it would be essential to 
keep up that pressure during the mandated negotiations 
now we have to be sure that the administration follows through 
by makin tough but reasonable demands and by getting some wins at 
the negotiating table wyden said 
</TEXT>
