<TEXT>
pan am corp said thursday it expects to secure 
at least 16 billion in financing by next week for its proposed 
36 billion bid for nwa inc parent of northwest airlines 
in a statement the parent company of pan american world airways 
said it was in active discussions with three major banks to 
secure financing and expects to receive final commitments by 
tuesday the deadline for bids set by nwa 
pan am said it was working with bankers trust co first 
national bank of chicago and security pacific national bank of los 
angeles on its offer for the nations fourthlargest carrier 
earlier pan am chairman thomas g plaskett said he would not 
seek wage concessions from northwest airline employees if his 
buyout is successful 
plaskett on a tour to secure backing for a bid told investors 
in a private meeting wednesday that pan am would have financing in 
place for an offer by tuesdays deadline 
plaskett said he is not contemplating layoffs of northwest union 
employees investors who attended the meeting said cooperation 
from northwests unions is considered key to the bid 
other likely bidders for eagan minnbased northwest include 
los angeles billionaire marvin davis whose first offer of 272 
billion was rejected and an investment group led by financier al 
checchi 
after davis made his bid the nwa board said it would explore 
restructuring alternatives the board said thursday it had 
appointed a special committee to oversee that process 
possible alternatives include acquisition of another company a 
partial or complete liquidation of the airline a repurchase of 
shares a special dividend or a sale of equity to third parties 
nwa stock closed thursday at 104 down 12 cents on the new 
york stock exchange 
in his meeting with investment fund managers plaskett outlined 
plans for his bid which would include sale of highyield notes 
totaling 16 billion and bank financing for the rest of the 36 
billion package 
he said the offer would be all cash and fully financed 
plaskett told investors he plans no sales of operating assets 
and no sale or leaseback of existing planes 
he said he is not assuming any revenue from a sale of 
northwests japanese real estate but expects to save 240 million 
by streamlining the new carriers corporate headquarters marketing 
operation maintenance and other support services 
industry analysts have been cautions about pan ams prospects 
because of its 900 million in debt 535 million in outstanding 
pension liabilities and continuing losses 
</TEXT>
